<p align="center">
<img border="0" src="Manual_pictures/Text.ico" width="30" height="30"><b>
<font color="#4682b4" size="5" face="Arial">Creating New Equations</font></b>
</p>

<b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
lang=EN-GB style='font-size:14.0pt;line-height:150%'>
 



<span lang=EN-GB>

<p>The Equation Editor supports creation of user’s own equations by opening of a template for an equation clicking on the New 
Equation button.  By positioning the cursor on one of the text  fields and double-clicking, 
a menu of all the operations 
available appears. When an operation is chosen, a new pair of text fields opens 
with the desired operator in between (in case of binary operations), a text field with the operator 
(in case of unary operation) or a function template with text fields for the function name, 
object name and time. </p>
<p>This can be 
continued further, until  the complete equation has been created. While it is being created, the equation is also 
displayed on the screen.</p>
<p>
Once completed by the editor, 
it is ready to be sent to the <i> Stage</i> where it can be used do define a property or behaviour of an object. 
Being on the <i>Stage</i>, the created equation can  be reused many times or  sent back to the Editor to be opened and changed. 
</p>

<p>See <a href = "open_eq.html">  Opening Existing Equations </a></p>


<font color="#4682b4" size="4" face="Arial"> <i>How to create an equation,  step by step example</i></font>
<p><i>To cerate the following equation:</i> </p>
<center>
<font size="4" color="#4682b4" face="Arial"> 
<p type="equation" version="2.0.0" replaceAppearance="equation" equationMathML="<apply><eq/><apply><mo>x</mo><ci>ME</ci><ci>t</ci></apply><apply><plus/><apply><mo>x</mo><ci>ME</ci><apply><minus/><ci>t</ci><cn>1</cn></apply></apply><apply><mo>Vx</mo><ci>ME</ci><ci>t</ci></apply></apply></apply>">
x(ME,t)=x(ME,t-1)+Vx(ME,t) </p></font> 
</center>



<i> first click on the New Equation button.
<ol>
<li>	Position the cursor on the left hand side of the Equation double-click  and choose <i>Function</i> from the menu.
<li>	Position the cursor on the field representing the name of the function and type in the name x.  
In the next text field type in object’s name ME and in the next one t, thus completing the left hand side. 
<li>	On the right hand side, position the cursor, double-click and choose '+' sign. 
After double-clicking on the left text field of the '+' sign, choose  Function from the menu. 
Then create a function in the similar way as explained in step 2.
<li>	For the right hand side of the '+' sign repeat the step 3 but instead of typing t , 
double-click in the third text field and choose the '-' sign from the menu. 
Complete the both sides of the '–' sign by typing in t and 1.

</ol></i>
<p>In order to get the equation right, it will have to be anticipated in order of precedence of its operators before starting. 
As explained in the introductory section, the equation is represented as a tree structure, so its structure will determine the order of the operations chosen.</p>

<p>The completed equation can be sent to the <i>Stage</i> to be used for defining an object's property or behavior.  
An equation is saved when an object using it is saved. </p>

